WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.080
So, my name is Davis Vaughn, I'm a software engineer at RStudio.

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:16.639
As Max said, this was supposed to be my beautiful e-poster that was going to be shown at the

00:00:16.639 --> 00:00:19.920
introduction, and it was not.

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:24.520
So I'm going to talk about this, but this looks horrible, so I'm just going to scrap

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:26.639
it entirely and start over.

00:00:26.639 --> 00:00:28.480
So this is a talk about two packages.

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:31.080
The first one is called Slider, and the second one is called Almanac.

00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:34.360
Yes, I'm going to do two packages in five minutes.

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:38.000
So Slider is a package for rolling and expanding windows.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.240
If you've ever used Zoo's RollApply or Sybil's Slide before, this is kind of the more supercharged

00:00:43.240 --> 00:00:44.639
version of those.

00:00:44.639 --> 00:00:51.599
So with the function Slide, you take a vector as input, you take a function that you want

00:00:51.599 --> 00:00:56.480
to apply to different sliding windows of that vector, and then you can control the window

00:00:56.480 --> 00:00:58.680
size with these extra arguments.

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:02.639
The only one I'm going to talk about today is the before argument.

00:01:02.639 --> 00:01:08.080
So here what this is saying is for each element, I'm going to take that current element of

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:14.279
the vector and look one element before as well, and that's going to make up my sliding

00:01:14.279 --> 00:01:15.279
window.

00:01:15.279 --> 00:01:19.320
So at the bottom here, there's another example of a different type of rolling window with

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:26.279
before equals two, and if yet, the animation is going, so you're seeing six back to four,

00:01:26.279 --> 00:01:30.760
ten back to five, and then with the expanding window, you can actually do things such as

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:35.120
cumulative sums or other different types of expanding ones.

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:40.800
So for that, you set before equals to infinity, which says give me the current element plus

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:43.559
everything before.

00:01:43.559 --> 00:01:47.919
This is supposed to have very, very, very similar syntax to per.

00:01:47.919 --> 00:01:49.800
Slide is very much like map.

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:53.959
In fact, the defaults are the same, and then it always returns a list.

00:01:53.959 --> 00:01:56.320
It's completely type and size stable.

00:01:56.320 --> 00:02:00.800
There are variants such as slide double, slide DFR, slide two, and PSlide, everything that

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:05.120
you might expect with per, there is in slide as well.

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:10.679
I'm more excited, though, about the fact that there's this idea of time-aware sliding built

00:02:10.679 --> 00:02:12.300
into this package.

00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:19.639
So slide index is this other function, and it allows you to pass this secondary date-like

00:02:19.639 --> 00:02:21.600
normally secondary index.

00:02:22.119 --> 00:02:27.360
What this means is that if you have this example here, and whether you can or cannot see it,

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:33.160
we've got a vector and then this secondary index where it's one, two, four, and then

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:34.160
five.

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:38.039
You can think of those like days of the month, the first, second, fourth, and fifth day of

00:02:38.039 --> 00:02:39.039
the month.

00:02:39.039 --> 00:02:45.399
If I want to take the current element and one day backwards, that might be kind of problematic

00:02:45.399 --> 00:02:49.199
here because we have an irregular gap in this series.

00:02:49.199 --> 00:02:53.119
But slide index is smart enough to know that when you're on the second day, you want a

00:02:53.119 --> 00:02:58.520
range of days one to two, and when you're on the fourth day, you want a range of days

00:02:58.520 --> 00:03:06.119
three to four, so it knows that in that third function call, you don't want day two.

00:03:06.119 --> 00:03:11.119
So slide doesn't know how to do this on its own because it doesn't have that extra index,

00:03:11.119 --> 00:03:16.600
but slide index does, kind of solving this completely new problem that's really useful

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:19.899
in time series analysis.

00:03:19.899 --> 00:03:22.080
So Almanac is a completely different package.

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:26.320
It kind of came out of a use case for slide where I really needed to control weekends

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:27.800
and holidays.

00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:34.080
So you can create kind of a holiday object with Almanac by starting with this base frequency,

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:37.880
like yearly or weekly, and then you add on these recurrence conditions.

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:42.720
For Labor Day, it happens in September, and it's on the first Monday in September.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:48.119
And then you can do fun things with that object, like say, what days are Labor Day?

00:03:48.119 --> 00:03:51.360
Returns yes or no.

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:56.119
I'm more excited for Almanac about these LuberDate extensions, though.

00:03:56.119 --> 00:03:59.000
We have this bDays object that you can use.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.960
So in the bottom right corner there, say that we're on Friday, and we want to go one day

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:03.960
ahead.

00:04:03.960 --> 00:04:07.139
You might use LuberDate days and just say plus one day.

00:04:07.139 --> 00:04:08.639
That takes you to Saturday.

00:04:08.639 --> 00:04:14.240
But in the business world, if I was on Friday, one business day ahead is actually Monday.

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:17.739
And if Monday is a holiday, it might actually be Tuesday.

00:04:17.739 --> 00:04:23.040
With Almanac, you can kind of bake in this scheduling logic of what are holidays, what

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:27.720
are weekends, what are the events that you're interested in, and then create this bDays

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:34.000
object in the bottom left with that schedule, which says skip over these events.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:39.160
So in the bottom right there, we have Friday plus one business day takes me to Monday.

00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:44.799
Lastly, Slider and Almanac are made to play very well together when you use slide index

00:04:44.799 --> 00:04:48.079
in conjunction with these bDays objects.

00:04:48.079 --> 00:04:53.720
You can say, for example, if I'm on Monday, look back one business day.

00:04:53.720 --> 00:04:59.040
That creates a range of Friday to Monday, and that kind of gives that nuanced difference

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:02.839
in that third function call there on the right.

00:05:02.839 --> 00:05:04.440
And that is Slider and Almanac.

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:05.440
Thank you.

00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:06.440
All right.

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:06.440


